name: Lampropeltis nigra (Yarrow, 1882)
occurrenceRemarks: Lampropeltis negra observed crossing road from west-to-east ahead of storm front. Found hiding behind tree 10ft from road, about a minute after driving by it. Third photo in-situ. Vibrated tail and cocked head in a strike pose once it knew it had been found. Made a single half-hearted bite attempt as I picked it up, then remained docile until releasing musk a few minutes later during measurements. 40.5” to cloaca, 46” to tail tip. 74deg F, cloudy, 90% humidity, thunder in distance. Last photos are screenshots of weather conditions at time of observation First Kingsnake and first AoR of the year for me!

identificationRemarks: This is an eastern black kingsnake (Lampropeltis nigra). Speckled kingsnake (Lampropeltis holbrooki) does not extend east of the Mississippi River. name: Lampropeltis nigra (Yarrow, 1882)
identificationRemarks: It looks as though this snake is on a glue trap. If it is still alive, you can use olive oil or cooking spray to gently and slowly dissolve the glue in order to remove them. These glue traps are also bad for a number of other reasons, including the fact that they indiscriminately catch and kill many other small, harmless native wildlife, including native amphibians and reptiles. Glue traps also do not work to address the root cause of a pest problem or infestation, and only capture individual pests. Instead of using these detrimental and outdated methods of control, one should look into more specific chemical treatments intended for the pest species at hand, and also seal off any cracks, gaps, or other openings in which other animals, such as snakes, can accidently encounter or end up in these.
